Because every derivation from the start–symbol S must begin with one of the five binary rules

  S → NT23 NT15  
  S → NT30 NT74  
  S → NT53 NT52  
  S → NT87 NT95  
  S → NT98 NT51  

the 45‑token input string would have to be split into two contiguous blocks whose lengths could be generated by the corresponding right‑hand non‑terminals.

Examining the lexical rules shows:

• NT30 can only generate a single terminal (t0 or t186) and nothing more; if we choose S → NT30 NT74 the first block would have length 1.  
  – NT74, however, can only expand either to one terminal (t211 or t224) or to exactly two non‑terminals (NT32 NT26).  
  – Neither NT32 nor NT26 can ultimately yield the required 44‑token second block because their own possible lexical yields are restricted to at most three different terminals each, and their binary expansions never re‑introduce enough breadth to reach 44 symbols.

• A similar length‑mismatch occurs for S → NT87 NT95 and S → NT98 NT51: each left member can contribute at most one or two terminals, forcing the right member to cover at least 43 terminals, which none of NT95 or NT51 can do (their productions bottom out after at most a handful of steps and terminals).

• For S → NT53 NT52 we would need NT53 to cover the 28‑token prefix that ends with the unique terminal t188 (only producible by NT53).  
  – Yet NT53 either produces that single t188 directly or expands to two non‑terminals, neither of which allows t188 to remain the 28th symbol while preserving the first 27 symbols; consequently this split is impossible.

• The only remaining possibility is S → NT23 NT15.  
  – To place the final t192 (token 45) under NT15 we must end with NT15 → NT72 NT48 → … t192, forcing NT72 to derive the 43 preceding tokens.  
  – NT72 in turn is limited to a single lexical item (t196) or to two non‑terminals (NT51 NT38 or NT99 NT62).  Tracing any of these branches shows that at most 3–4 terminals can be produced before reaching only lexical leaves, far short of the required 43.

Because none of the five mandatory splits can match the 45‑token length of the string with the production capacities of their corresponding non‑terminals, the string cannot be derived from S.

Hence the given grammar does not generate the string.
